  1. What variables might be related to Commuting times? Load the CommuteStLouis and CommuteAtlanta dataframes from Lock5data into R and combine them into one dataset using rbind(1stDataset, 2ndDataset). Combine and create a basic plot visualizing the relationship between Commute time and and another, reasonable, variable.

    First, lets look at the relationship between all the variables. Here we can see that commute Time has a clear positive trend with the Distance traveled.

pairs(commute)

Lets get a closer look at the relationship. 
ggplot(commute, aes(x=Time,  y=Distance)) + geom_point() + ggtitle("Relationship between Commmute Time and Distance")

  1. Do these variables appear to be correlated? Demonstrate this visually. How well does your explanatory variable appear to predict Commute times?

    As explained above, we can see a positive trend with commute Time and Distance. We should create the linear model to see the relationship more clearly.

ggplot(commute, aes(x=Time,  y=Distance)) + geom_point() + ggtitle("Relationship between Commute Time and Distance") + geom_smooth(method = "lm")

lm.commute <- lm(Distance ~ Time, data = commute)
summary(lm.commute)
##

## 
## Residual standard error: 7.195 on 998 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.6702, Adjusted R-squared:  0.6699 
## F-statistic:  2028 on 1 and 998 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16
When we look at the summary of the linear model, we can see that the trend is very strong. With a p-value so low along with a correlation of 0.8186852, we can reject the null hypothesis and conclude that there is a significant relationship between `Time` and `Distance`.
  1. That’s all well and good, but you haven’t slept in three days (#thesisthings) and have begun to forget what all this means. Label your axes and give your graph a brilliant and inspiring title (and maybe an appropriate caption if you’d like). Don’t forget to cite your source somewhere…plagiarism isn’t cool, and someone deserves credit for collecting all this data.
ggplot(commute, aes(x=Time,  y=Distance)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method = "lm") + labs(title="Relationship between Commute Time and Distance", subtitle="CommuteAtlanta and CommuteStLouis datasets from Lock5Data package", y="Distance (in miles)", x="Time (in minutes)")

  1. This plot is good…but is it graphically excellent? Experiment with additional ggplot options to ensure your visualization meets the first 3 Principles of Graphical Excellence. You can reference the following cheat sheet for inspiration: https://www.rstudio.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/ggplot2-cheatsheet.pdf.

  2. There is still one more principle (excluding truthful) to follow before our visualization can be truly graphically excellent: right now, it’s still only bivariate! Add a layer(s) of data to your visualization. (Hint: How can we group this data effectively?)

ggplot(commute, aes(x=Time,  y=Distance)) + geom_point(aes(col=City), size = 2) + geom_smooth(method = "lm", col = "black", size = 0.5) + labs(title="Relationship between Commute Time and Distance", subtitle="CommuteAtlanta and CommuteStLouis datasets from Lock5Data package, grouped by Gender", y="Distance (in miles)", x="Time (in minutes)") + facet_grid(Sex ~ .) + scale_colour_brewer(palette = "Paired")
